      <h1>Origins</h1>
      <br></br>
      <img class="about_img" src="{{static '/img/mother_and_me.jpg'}}"></img>
      <p class="caption">
      My mom and I when I was but a babe
      </p>
      <br></br>
      <div class="text_section">
      <p>
    My name is Alberto or Tristan depending on when you met me.  The latter is my middle name which I started going by since early this year.  Take your pick!
      </p>
      <p>
    My story really begins a while ago, long before my birth. It was in 1979 that one could mark the beginning of the Salvadoran Civil War, the details of which are really not that special for a third world country often ensnared in these kinds of bloody affairs. My father was 17 at the time, living in a lush rural area with a partial high school education and not much to his name. After experiencing first hand the seemingly never-ending violence and deaths around him, he immigrated to Mexico to avoid being drafted into a probable death by guerilleros fighting against an oppressive government regime.
      </p>
      <p>
    It was there he met my mother and started a life together. My mother is from the state of Chihuahua (yes, like the dog), which is basically straight south of Texas. Not long after, they made the important decision to immigrate one more country up and come to the United States in 1983. The San Francisco 49er’s were pretty amazing at the time and my parents have been fans ever since!
      </p>
      <p>
    I had the good fortune to be born in 1990 in Los Angeles, CA, avoiding much of the relative poverty and lack of opportunity my parents had to face. I was raised my entire life in Southern California, instilled with my parents undying belief that with proper education and hard work one could make anything of themselves in this country.  It is against this backdrop that much of my life took form and shape.
      </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="row">
    <div class="col-md-8 col-md-offset-2">
      <h1>Childhood</h1>
      <br></br>
      <img class="about_img" src="{{static '/img/siblings.JPG'}}"></img>
      <p class="caption">
      My siblings and I when we were kids.
      </p>
      <br></br>
      <div class="text_section">
      <p>
    According to my mother, I nearly died at birth due to suffocation.  That may have killed a few brain cells.  I'd like to think I would have been a frikkin' genius were it not for that little natal snafu!
      </p>
      <p>
    I was raised my entire life in Southern California, bouncing around around from city to city.  Just off the top of my head, this includes places with names as wonderful as the aforementioned Los Angeles, Ontario, Corona, Fontana, Norco, and Rancho Cucamonga.  Rancho Cucamonga is the last place I lived in and where my parents currently reside.  As far as I know, the only reasons someone would know of this town are:
        <ul>
          <li> in one particular Simpson's episode, Krusty the Clown has Rancho Cucamonga as number 3 in his Top 10 Funny City Names list</li>
          <li> it is the town the movie Next Friday is based in </li>
          <li> it is also the town that the excellent (well, at least for a couple of seasons) comedy show Workaholics takes place in.</li>
        </ul>
     </p>
      <p>
    My elementary school days were spent at Corona Elementary School in Ontario, CA.  I didn't realize it at the time, but apparently it was not a very "good" neighborhood.  It would only be years later that I would realize a school with 95%+ Hispanic and Black students was not the norm experience for most kids in the United States.  Interestingly enough, my first encounter with drugs of any sort was when the one white kid at school brought weed to school.
      </p>
      <p>
    My mother was what the best selling author Amy Chua might call a "tiger mom".  She was a loving and doting stay-at-home mother who did everything for me and my siblings, but she was also a pretty strict mother when it came to schooling and education.  People look at me today and think I'm smart when really I just had good habits drilled into me at a young age.
      </p>
      <p>
    My father was / is a truck driver and, for as long as I can remember, worked long hours out on the road to make sure we never lacked for material possessions.  Yet, despite that, he always seemed to have an unbounded sense of energy and happiness to hang out and stuff.
      </p>
      <p>
    Middle school was an interesting turning point in my life.  I had "won" an interdistrict lottery transfer, which granted my mother the privilege of driving an extra 30-40 minutes to take me to a better middle school.  This also meant I knew no one at school.  Still, I made some classically nerdy friends with whom I could play Magic the Gathering, Yu-Gi-Oh, and read comic books with in short order.  It was also around this time I started doing Kenpo Karate, something I would eventually get a black belt in.  I was also a pretty good flag football defensive end and was on the school's journalism team.
      </p>
      <p>
    High school was another interdistrict transfer to a better school, another new place with thousands of students of whom I knew no one initially.  I played some football but was really too scrawny to be of much use until later in high school when I started lifting weights.  Lifting weights turned me from a skinny, acne ridden kid to a decently swole, acne ridden kid which was nice.  I also wrestled on the varsity team here.  I was also involved in a few random school clubs people tell you to join because it looks good on your college applications.  I ended up graduating valedictorian and having a lot of fun along the way.
      </p>
