      <br></br>
      <div class="text_section">
      <p>
    Upon graduation, I moved to New York City because “why the hell not?” seemed like a perfectly valid reason at the time (still does, actually). I got a job working as a data scientist at Match Media Group, which owns many beloved online dating sites like OkCupid and Tinder. According to a <a href="https://www.glassdoor.com/List/Best-Jobs-in-America-LST_KQ0,20.htm">recent article</a> put forth by GlassDoor, data scientist is number 1 so that’s kind of neat.
      </p>
      <p>
    However, I really missed suffering through my math and computer science classes and needed to be abused just one last time. I ended up getting my master’s degree in computer science at Columbia University. Being student poor in NYC while trying to make the last of your savings from your previous job stretch as far as possible was quite the experience.  There's the starving artist, then there's the starving engineering student.
      </p>
      <p>
    My first job out of grad school was at Shutterstock (not to be confused with Shutterfly), where I helped solve interesting search related problems using statistical machine learning tools.  As a machine learning engineer there, I worked on various projects including creating a new spellcheck service, working on a new machine learning based search ranking system, implementing an automated image keyword tagger, and a celebrity identification application.
      </p>
      <p>
    I am currently on hiatus from any kind of work, but will soon be joining the fine folks at SquareSpace as one of their first machine learning engineers.  We will be responsible for building out the machine learning infrastructure there and bringing data-driven solutions out to the forefront that can improve the user experience for the millions of people who use SquareSpace as the basis of their online identity.
      </p>
